00:06:52.149 --> 00:07:00.129
The difference between these two and, and this is what we're
looking at is that the, the tension as I would, as I would,

00:07:00.129 --> 00:07:08.600
from a physics point of view, between 90 percent on end and
90 percent the other, is what I call a market opportunity.

00:07:08.600 --> 00:07:16.689
So this is where there's going to be an enormous amount of
content that needs to be produced for nonfictional content.

00:07:16.689 --> 00:07:23.219
Now what, what I mean by that, that's the how tos, that's
the historical, that's the documentary style pieces.

00:07:23.220 --> 00:07:25.290
These are all things that people are going to be interested in

00:07:25.290 --> 00:07:31.770
I believe that we're going to get to a point where
we assume that we can learn things through video.

00:07:31.769 --> 00:07:37.109
You know we're going to be a little perturbed if we want to learn
how to do calculus or we want to learn how to you know a lot

00:07:37.110 --> 00:07:39.580
of other things and we can't find a video on it.

00:07:39.579 --> 00:07:44.099
And, and it's really, really important because we
can actually assimilate the information much quicker

00:07:44.100 --> 00:07:46.560
and much younger when we get it in video format.

00:07:46.560 --> 00:07:53.079
I, my daughter when she was 10 I was asking her what she
was learning in school and she was, and she said, well,

00:07:53.079 --> 00:07:55.759
I been really learning a lot about string theory.

00:07:55.759 --> 00:07:57.709
You know she's, she's 10 years old, you know.

00:07:57.709 --> 00:07:59.899
And I said, so, so what is string theory?

00:07:59.899 --> 00:08:01.239
And she went into describing it.

00:08:01.240 --> 00:08:05.800
There's this, you know there's quantum physics and then
there's the big bang and, and they don't really get along,

00:08:05.800 --> 00:08:09.480
but there's this theory that if you keep on going into
the molecules and you go in, you keep on going in,

00:08:09.480 --> 00:08:11.150
you end up with little strings of energy.

00:08:11.149 --> 00:08:14.529
And this ties together the big bang
and the, and the, and she, I mean,

00:08:14.529 --> 00:08:16.569
she described it better than most college students.

00:08:16.569 --> 00:08:19.959
You know and I asked her you know how she learned that.

00:08:19.959 --> 00:08:22.099
And she was like, Nova.

00:08:22.100 --> 00:08:25.930
You know and, and there was this Nova thing
on, on string theory that tied it all together.

00:08:25.930 --> 00:08:31.720
Now she's a 10 year old that understands
something that most graduate students had a,

00:08:31.720 --> 00:08:35.800
would have a hard time describing
because she got it visually.

00:08:35.799 --> 00:08:41.169
She didn't have to have her ability to accumulate the
ability to read and all the, all the historical stuff

00:08:41.169 --> 00:08:43.599
to be able to actually absorb that information.

00:08:43.600 --> 00:08:49.149
Because of that, there's going to be an enormous
pressure, especially when we look at elearning

00:08:49.149 --> 00:08:52.500
for lots and lots and lots of video content.

00:08:52.500 --> 00:08:55.639
So another thing to think about
when you're when you're starting

00:08:55.639 --> 00:08:59.259
to put this stuff together is the frequency
of the kind of thing that you're doing.

00:08:59.259 --> 00:09:02.230
And I'm really only talking about two different frequencies.

00:09:02.230 --> 00:09:05.610
Because in my opinion, these are the only two that work.

00:09:05.610 --> 00:09:08.909
Which is either once a week or once a day.

00:09:08.909 --> 00:09:11.870
Once a day you really have to be committed.

00:09:11.870 --> 00:09:13.879
That you're going to, you're going to actually produce that.

00:09:13.879 --> 00:09:16.960
We've tried once a day and it's painful.

00:09:16.960 --> 00:09:23.840
So you can do it but you have to really think about
how to build an efficient pipeline to make it work.

00:09:23.840 --> 00:09:27.560
Once a week is probably the best if
you're getting started in podcasting.

00:09:27.559 --> 00:09:31.149
There's a lot of people that put out pod
casts kind of whenever they finish them.

00:09:31.149 --> 00:09:33.939
Or they put a couple out, then they
wait for a couple months and they,

00:09:33.940 --> 00:09:38.280
and the big thing is you're not really
going to build a listener ship that way.

00:09:38.279 --> 00:09:39.699
You're not, or a viewer ship that way.

00:09:39.700 --> 00:09:42.150
You're not going to build a following unless you're regular.

00:09:42.149 --> 00:09:46.350
And I say that as we, we've gone up and down
of being regular, you know back and forth.

00:09:46.350 --> 00:09:49.110
We, we do it mostly once a week for most of our shows.

00:09:49.110 --> 00:09:53.500
But that is the, that's a much better approach

00:09:53.500 --> 00:10:00.669
And so you, the key when I talk about that is that you
want to think about how you're going to design a set of shows.

00:10:00.669 --> 00:10:06.819
For instance, our new shows now, from learning
from all the other podcasts we've done is

00:10:06.820 --> 00:10:15.230
that we generally have four shows done in the can,
figured out before we turn the, turn the spicket on.

00:10:15.230 --> 00:10:20.950
You know we're, we make sure that we have a buffer kind
of built in before we get going to make sure that we get,

00:10:20.950 --> 00:10:23.060
that we have a little bit of room to start to work in.

00:10:23.059 --> 00:10:25.149
Then we try to keep that buffer going.

00:10:25.149 --> 00:10:31.600
MacBreak, that many of you have seen, has
actually only been recorded about four times.

00:10:31.600 --> 00:10:33.940
So to give you kind of a sense of how much we buffer.

00:10:33.940 --> 00:10:34.030
( Laughter )

00:10:34.029 --> 00:10:40.709
We, we can typically shoot 12 to 18 MacBreaks in a day.

00:10:40.710 --> 00:10:43.990
And so, so those things get all you know buffered together.

00:10:43.990 --> 00:10:46.000
And that's one of the things that we do, we do a lot of.

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:49.679
And one of the things to make this work is efficiency.

00:10:49.679 --> 00:10:53.849
Now if you start to think, and I'll
get back to efficiency in a second.

00:10:53.850 --> 00:10:58.269
When you start to think about how you build your
podcast, you really have obviously two podcasts.

00:10:58.269 --> 00:10:59.210
You have audio.

00:10:59.210 --> 00:11:03.050
And audio, one of the things you have to think
about is what are people doing when they're,

00:11:03.049 --> 00:11:05.490
when they're watching or listening to your show.

00:11:05.490 --> 00:11:07.169
With audio, they're working.

00:11:07.169 --> 00:11:11.649
They might be stuck in a traffic
jam, if they're in San Francisco.

00:11:11.649 --> 00:11:16.490
And also they might be just walking,
exercising, so on so forth.

00:11:16.490 --> 00:11:21.830
What this equates to is a much longer
format, a long length, 30 to 90 minutes.

00:11:21.830 --> 00:11:29.900
We have gone back and forth with This Week in Media going
short, long, figuring out and for a while we thought

00:11:29.899 --> 00:11:32.269
that maybe we should really be
doing it for 30 or 40 minutes.

00:11:32.269 --> 00:11:33.689
Like we should do a really short piece.

00:11:33.690 --> 00:11:37.950
People told us well it takes me about 35
minutes to get to work, that's all I want.

00:11:37.950 --> 00:11:40.940
And so for about two or three months,
I would ask every person who said

00:11:40.940 --> 00:11:43.520
that they listened to the show how long they wanted it.

00:11:43.519 --> 00:11:45.590
You know do they care about the long ones or the short ones.

00:11:45.590 --> 00:11:50.740
And almost every, everyone to a person said they didn't
care how long it was or that they liked the long one.

00:11:50.740 --> 00:11:53.080
And the reason is that they're
just playing it in the background.

00:11:53.080 --> 00:11:53.740
They don't really care.

00:11:53.740 --> 00:11:55.080
It's just filling up time.

00:11:55.080 --> 00:11:58.250
You know it's just, it's just like NPR, it's
just something that goes in the background.

00:11:58.250 --> 00:12:03.960
So you can do a, a much longer format with
audio and people will be pretty understanding.

00:12:03.960 --> 00:12:05.810
With video, they're sitting in front of their computer.

00:12:05.809 --> 00:12:12.419
They're watching their AppleTV or they're watching it on
their iPod, their phone, their iPhone, all of those things.

00:12:12.419 --> 00:12:19.889
And what this equates to and this is the difference, is the
audio you're really having it, it's a secondary activity.

00:12:19.889 --> 00:12:21.500
It's not really happening in the foreground.

00:12:21.500 --> 00:12:26.490
Video is a primary activity which means that you
really are looking at three to eight minutes.

00:12:26.490 --> 00:12:30.590
This is really the sweet spot when
you're actually doing video work.

00:12:30.590 --> 00:12:36.740
A lot of people think about doing podcasts that are 15
minutes long and 20, you know 15, 20, 25, 30 minutes long.

00:12:36.740 --> 00:12:38.850
But we have to sit there and watch it.

00:12:38.850 --> 00:12:40.389
You know and there's two problems with that.

00:12:40.389 --> 00:12:47.149
One is that A, you're sucking up, now you're taking
away my actual work time to get this stuff done.

00:12:47.149 --> 00:12:52.699
The second thing is that you're working
typically on a lower budget than Lost.

00:12:52.700 --> 00:12:58.120
You know or ER and, and it's gotta be
really good if it's going to last 20 minutes.

00:12:58.120 --> 00:13:02.679
You know that's, there's, there's not many
things you can do on a low budget that,

00:13:02.679 --> 00:13:05.799
that is worth actually putting that together.

00:13:05.799 --> 00:13:10.490
So, so anyway you, you really especially
you want to keep it you know simple.

00:13:10.490 --> 00:13:17.620
There's a quote that has been referred to, back to both Mark
Twain and Abraham Lincoln, depending on who you talk to.

00:13:17.620 --> 00:13:23.080
Which is that it's better to keep one's mouth shut
and look foolish than to open it and remove all doubt.

00:13:23.080 --> 00:13:27.129
So this applies directly to our video of making
sure that we move through things quickly,

00:13:27.129 --> 00:13:30.659
try to keep it short and not hang too long.

