Another thing that you have to pay attention
to is the scale of what you're shooting now.

00:13:36.399 --> 00:13:39.909
So what you see in the lower corner is standard definition.

00:13:39.909 --> 00:13:44.360
That's bigger than a lot of what you would
normally put on your iPod, the little 320 by 240,

00:13:44.360 --> 00:13:47.680
although now you can put much larger formats on there.

00:13:47.679 --> 00:13:50.069
But that's standard definition.

00:13:50.070 --> 00:13:57.030
720p is kind of, that's really the, the largest
size you're going to put on an AppleTV right now

00:13:57.029 --> 00:14:05.629
and 1080p is pretty much full broadcast, well
full, I mean that's theatrical release size.

00:14:05.629 --> 00:14:11.549
But one of the things that's really is that you
can shoot all of these fairly inexpensively now.

00:14:11.549 --> 00:14:20.689
There's not, I would, if you feel like you're producing
content that is worth keeping around and hopefully

00:14:20.690 --> 00:14:23.110
if you're building a podcast, that's what you're doing.

00:14:23.110 --> 00:14:27.379
You know if you don't think its worth keeping
around then you should find another podcast.

00:14:27.379 --> 00:14:33.389
But if you really feel like its worth having, one of
the things that I would highly consider is getting rid

00:14:33.389 --> 00:14:36.519
of the DVD camera and going ahead with an HDV camera.

