00:42:25.880 --> 00:42:29.880
So the first thing is there's really
two types of compression that's going

00:42:29.880 --> 00:42:33.110
on anytime you're doing any, any work like this.

00:42:33.110 --> 00:42:35.360
And that's the first one is spatial compression.

00:42:35.360 --> 00:42:42.220
And what you're really looking at here with spatial
compression is what pixels look alike in a single frame.

00:42:42.219 --> 00:42:47.579
So as I'm looking at this frame, the blues are going to be
start, it's going to start grouping those blues together.

00:42:47.579 --> 00:42:49.039
It's going to group the grays together.

00:42:49.039 --> 00:42:51.550
It's going to group the purples in Leo's shirt together.

00:42:51.550 --> 00:42:55.970
It's going to group all of that stuff together and it'll
find as many pixels as it can to group those together.

00:42:55.969 --> 00:43:00.949
And if it can't, the higher you turn the compression,
the more it forces those pixels to be the same.

00:43:00.949 --> 00:43:06.449
It says, well they're close enough, I'm going to make this
block all, all the same number of, the same kind of pixel.

00:43:06.449 --> 00:43:09.849
That's where you get blocks by the way is
because it, when you start turning it up,

00:43:09.849 --> 00:43:13.049
it forces those pixels into, in to corrals.

00:43:13.050 --> 00:43:17.150
So this is one, one piece of the compression technology.

00:43:17.150 --> 00:43:19.610
The second is temporal compression.

00:43:19.610 --> 00:43:24.240
And the temporal compression is really
looking at what changes between frames.

00:43:24.239 --> 00:43:30.129
So if I look at this frame and then I go down
a couple more frames, between these key frames,

00:43:30.130 --> 00:43:33.140
and that's what you're looking at,
when you're looking in, in QuickTime,

00:43:33.139 --> 00:43:37.269
what you're looking at there is it,
you'll see this little key frame number.

00:43:37.269 --> 00:43:39.880
A 12 or 24 or whatever.

00:43:39.880 --> 00:43:45.680
What it's saying is I'm going to lay an entire
frame down no matter what, what's happening.

00:43:45.679 --> 00:43:52.919
And, and then its gotta have, these are kind of like
if you're thinking about climbing up a mountain,

00:43:52.920 --> 00:43:55.090
it's where you're driving your spikes into the ground.

00:43:55.090 --> 00:43:56.320
In, into the wall.

00:43:56.320 --> 00:43:59.140
You know, so you're going to get up to a certain
height and you're going to go I'm going to drive one in

00:43:59.139 --> 00:44:01.269
and then I'm going to walk up a little bit further.

00:44:01.269 --> 00:44:04.789
So what it's doing is adding these key frames in between.

00:44:04.789 --> 00:44:10.150
The further out you put those key frames, the
more efficient your compression is going to become.

00:44:10.150 --> 00:44:19.019
