00:44:40.150 --> 00:44:42.190
Now a lot of people don't connect these two things.

00:44:42.190 --> 00:44:45.880
One of the things you'll notice about a lot of
our podcasts is the cameras don't move a lot.

00:44:45.880 --> 00:44:50.349
The reason they don't move a lot is
because it, every time you move the camera,

00:44:50.349 --> 00:44:52.440
it has to add what you call a natural key frame.

00:44:52.440 --> 00:44:55.840
It has to go, well too much has
changed in this, in the scene.

00:44:55.840 --> 00:44:59.720
And so I'm going to add another key frame
to make sure that things are based on it.

00:44:59.719 --> 00:45:03.459
If you move the camera too slowly,
and you have big wide distances

00:45:03.460 --> 00:45:06.119
between key frames, that's when you start to see a tear.

00:45:06.119 --> 00:45:09.289
You know because it'll tear because
it doesn't realize that enough,

00:45:09.289 --> 00:45:11.329
you know it doesn't realize that
things have been moving too much.

00:45:11.329 --> 00:45:13.659
And so you start to see artifacts.

00:45:13.659 --> 00:45:15.339
So that's what's actually happening there.

00:45:15.340 --> 00:45:18.500
So we don't, what we try to avoid is a lot of slow pans.

00:45:18.500 --> 00:45:23.699
And we also try to avoid the camera moving when we,
when we, we'd rather edit, cut from one frame, you know.

00:45:23.699 --> 00:45:26.639
Cut from one camera to another than move the camera around.

00:45:26.639 --> 00:45:34.109
The other thing that is will really kill
your temporal compression is handheld shots.

00:45:34.110 --> 00:45:37.960
So its, it looks really cool, but you
gotta be really careful about that

00:45:37.960 --> 00:45:41.090
because the handheld shot defeats
all of the temporal compression.

00:45:41.090 --> 00:45:44.480
And so that's going to be something that's
going to make your file literally five

00:45:44.480 --> 00:45:49.159
